animal.name: Cookie
animal.description:
COURTESY POST:

Cookie is a 12 year old Maltese mix that weighs about 9 lbs, he’s such a sweetheart and gives tiny little kisses! 

Cookie is blind and diabetic but still has such an explorer's personality, he’ll walk around the whole house teaching himself the layout.

When he wakes up he’s trained to let out a few barks so you know he’s ready to go potty. He does the same thing to let you know when he’s hungry or thirsty and once he’s gotten what he’s asking for he goes right back to bed,

He absolutely loves being held and being with another human or even another dog, if you let him sleep with you he buries himself right into you.

Cookie would do amazing in any home where he receives daily attention and has at least one person who’s attentive to his needs. Because of his conditions he needs a little more direct care than some other dogs but it’s an extremely rewarding feeling to bond with a dog who absolutely loves and needs you.

He receives insulin twice daily within 30 minutes of breakfast and dinner and also gets eye drops as necessary. If you are interested in Cookie, please complete the on-line application that can be found on our website: 

www.adoptmerescue.org or contact us for more information.

animal.name: SPARKY
animal.description:
Sparky’s Story: 
“Hello my name is Sparky. I am an 11 year old husky/Shepard mix. 

I have sad tale with a possible happy-ending! 

On 6/29/22, I was found in La Mirada, CA by a nice lady who tried three times to capture me. I was scared of her and every other human who was trying to capture me because I had been on my own running the street for more than three days. She turned out to be a very nice lady. 

She took me to the doctors because my paws were hurting me. Turns out I just wore my paw pads out after all the days alone on the hot pavement. I think cost her a lot of money because she kept telling me I was “lucky I was as cute” over and over again. ?

The nice lady found my owner of 11 years. It’s the only home I have ever known. It breaks my heart to say but my owner doesn’t want me back ?. Apparently, my owner can not take care me anymore and can’t keep me from getting out. I feel sad, but those fireworks just scared me so bad. 

Thankfully, the nice lady is letting me stay with her temporarily instead of being in a loud and scary shelter. Old guys like me don’t last long at the shelter.

I am happy not be in the shelter but NOW I want to find my forever home - is that with you and your family? Please help keep me out of the shelter. 

I am a good boy. I promise. I just need lots love and attention. I am very nervous and anxious when you first meet me but with TIME and PATIENCE I will warm up to you and then become your shadow. I don’t like to be left alone right now but the nice lady is working on that with me. 

I am extremely smart - I should have been named Einstein or Houdini! I guess that’s the Husky in me. 
I love pets and cuddles after I settle in with you. I just learned how to play and I love it! 
I get along great with other dogs big or small (see the video of me with my temp foster brother). I not sure how I feel about cats yet. 
However, sudden movements make me nervous. 
I am fully vaccinated as of 7/17/22. 
I am neutered. 
My doggie doctor said I have no major health issues or abnormalities. 

Contact the lady who is caring for me if you want to meet me?! Her name is Stephanie Rigoli. 562-477-0061.”

animal.name: SNOW
animal.description:
Snow is a 2-3 -year old German Shepherd/Golden Retriever-mix female. When you meet her  you would think she is a Golden Retriever, as she looks like a Golden, but she behaves more like a protective German Shepherd. She weighs about 75-80 pounds and has a beautiful fluffy coat. Once she settles in, she is very devoted to her people and loyal. She is a medium-energy dog that enjoys being with her people, follows them everywhere and loves to lie right next to her person - she is pretty much a velcro dog. You can tell that she loves going for walks, because  she puts on quite a display of happiness and excitement by the door. On her walks she can be difficult and reactive, like a German Shepherd, so her future owner needs to be strong and healthy (someone with back and shoulder issues can't handle Snow) to be able to walk her; she will also need obedience training, so the owner could learn how to handle her during their daily walks.

Inside the house Snow is almost perfect and very well-behaved. She is not destructive when left alone, does not try to escape the yard, is not a fence jumper and not a digger. She loves toys and her favorite game is chasing balls. When she is happy she loves running in circles in the yard - and she can run pretty fast! She knows the “Sit”, “Down” and “Paw” commands and loves getting belly rubs and giving her paw. This gorgeous girl is very affectionate and likes giving kisses.
She is wonderful with other dogs after a slow introduction. In her foster home she has been living with small- and large-size dogs and does well with them all - at first she doesn’t play much, but once she settles in and feels that she is a part of the family, she starts playing with other dogs. Snow has the instincts of a German Shepherd and will protect her person and her house. In her foster home she is allowed to sleep anywhere she wants, but she prefers to sleep right by the door all night and will warn you if needed.

Due to her being a protective dog, she will bark and might lunge/snap at visiting dogs and people. The solution her foster mom has found is to put Snow in a crate from where she can see the people and can sniff the visiting dogs; she will probably bark for 5-10 minutes, but once she knows the visitors are harmless she chills out and lays down. When Snow is done barking and chilling for 10-15min, her foster mom opens the crate door, so Snow could smell the visitors; once that’s done, Snow is usually good to go. She is generally quiet, but being an alert dog she will bark when hearing noises. Snow is very housebroken, knows how to use a doggie door and is crate-trained. She loves going for car rides and has no problem jumping into the back of a SUV, but during the ride she will bark at things that arrest her attention.
Even though she is good with all-size dogs in her foster home, Snow is not a dog to take to dog parks.
What type of home does Snow need?
* An adult home with no kids, with another dog OR as an only-dog. She is more into people than dogs, but will enjoy having a friend too.
* The adopter needs to commit to doing obedience work and leash-training in order to adopt her
If you are willing to work with her and be patient, Snow is a wonderful, sweet dog.
We are located in Los Angeles. If interested in Snow please submit an application on our website, www.angelsbarkrescue.org

animal.name: TESSA
animal.description:
Tessa is a sweet, female German Shepherd about 6-8 years old, about 80 pounds . This adorable girl spent 7 months in a shelter. We rescued her on  the day she was to be euthanized.
Tessa is a confident, well-balanced soul, and loves people. She gets attached quickly, and follows her person everywhere. She's a “velcro” dog, but also enjoys her space and easily settles into "downtime."
Tessa is totally housebroken, and has no problem being alone if her person leaves. She is not destructive and rarely barks. She is good alone in a secure yard, and won't try to escape by digging or trying to jump a fence.
Tessa LOVES going for daily walks and does well on leash. She doesn’t pull much after a few minutes of intense sniffing, and with some basic training she will be a perfect dog. She will definitely enjoy an active owner, but also has no problem being mellow and napping on her bed.
She is always happy to see people (more than other pets). Tessa enjoys car rides: she'll look out the window, or lies down and remain calm.
She loves to be brushed and did great at the groomer. She also did great at her vet exam, and gave kisses to the doctor. 
Tessa loves bones and toys. She likes playing fetch: she brings the ball back, and drops it. 

Her Previous Foster Mom wrote:
"Tessa is always happy - loves to follow you around, and has been great with older kids (10 yr. olds). She knows “Sit” and  “Stop” and is practicing “Stay." She is not protective of toys, bones or her food bowl. She sits for the leash to be put on. She likes to fetch but after a few throws she likes to lie down with the ball. She’s a sure-footed explorer and it’s entertaining to watch her squeeze through small spaces - she doesn’t realize how big she is! She’s never tried to jump a wall, or escape. Her nose investigates EVERYTHING. She’s good around people's food – she doesn’t beg. By 8pm she’s down for the count and sleeps through the night. She will go in her crate during the day for a couple of hours, if needed. Tessa reacts towards unfamiliar dogs during walks and seems to show a prey drive towards small animals - a home with no cats is recommended. She’d benefit from an experienced owner who will work on consistent obedience. Tessa’s ideal home would have to have a secure yard, and grass to roll around in.
Tessa is a wonderful dog! Someone will surely be blessed to have her in their life. She is located in Los Angeles.--

animal.name: Ozzie
animal.description:
*PLEASE NOTE: This doggie belongs to another rescue called Rovers Retreat Rescue Organization. We are just posted as courtesy post to help. If you have any questions please email them directly by emailing them at roversretreat.org@gmail.com 

*PLEASE NOTE: Ozzie does shed. The first step in the adoption process is to fill out an adoption application on our website: roversretreat.org *

Meet Ozzie. Ozzie is an adorable 1-year-old possible West Highland Terrier / poodle mix who is as sweet as can be! While he looks like he could be a labradoodle, please note that he DOES shed. 
Ozzie came into rescue when his owners had to move into an apartment that did not allow big dogs. He has spent the past few weeks settling in at his foster home and is now ready to find his forever family.

Ozzie is a very happy boy who loves his people. He sleeps all night in his foster mom’s bed and is quite the cuddle buddy. He is definitely a velcro dog and will follow his foster mom around the house seeking attention throughout the day. He is a great work-from-home buddy and will just sleep at his fosters’ feet while she works during the day, or will pick up a toy and entertain himself. 

Ozzie is getting a few daily walks and greatly enjoys his time out in the neighborhood. He is still getting used to walking on leash, but he’s getting better every day. He gets anywhere from 2-5 miles of walking a day and is the best fit for an active person ready to give him plenty of daily activity and adventure! He would be a perfect hiking buddy, as well. 

Ozzie has been a pretty good houseguest in his foster home, although he is a young dog still so he still needs to be watched closely at times. He has done very well with potty training and will go out into the yard when he needs to go potty. Ozzie does have his mischievous times. After all, he is a puppy! He will find things to chew on if left unattended and he doesn’t get the exercise he needs. It is important that Ozzie’s forever family give him plenty of exercise, puppy proof, as well as to not leave him alone with full reign of the house at first. He is a very smart boy, so as long as he is set up for success he will learn very quickly what you want from him. 

Ozzie has been working on his interactions with other dogs since he is being fostered in a home without other animals, and he is getting better! He can be reactive on leash when walking sometimes but this has been less and less frequent as he has settled in more. With a new change he will likey be reactive when seeing other dogs, but with gentle corrections and time this will get better as it did when he settled in at his foster home. Ozzie would do best in a home without any other animals with owners dedicated to training and continting to work with him on his social skills. 

Ozzie is eager to find his forever family with people who love walks, play, and cuddles as much as he does. If you are interested in adopting Ozzie please fill out an adoption application on our website: Roversretreat.org

Any questions can be directed to Sydney@roversretreat.org

*PLEASE NOTE: Ozzie’s adoption fee is $500 and he is being fostered in Northridge*

animal.description:
Meet LAFM Decker! 

Hello, I am Decker! I was born in Mexico and was transported up to Los Angeles as a puppy — and now I am looking for a forever home to call my own. I am abut 2 years old. My trainer would describe me as a very sweet and sometimes shy boy who loves to play and have fun, once I feel comfortable. It does take me a little bit of time to warm up to new people in my life, but if I am afraid I will let you know so that you can help me through it. I would do best in a calm home with no small children, hopefully with a patient parent who can help me continue to learn to be the best boy that I know I can be. I love to play with other dogs and would do great in a house as the only dog or with a sibling dog that can help to show me the ropes. I am very respectful with other dogs and know how to give space when they ask for it, so I would ask for the same in return! Sometimes loud noises and the city environment can scare me, but I have been working very hard with my trainer and I doing so much better! I can be scared of any new encounters, but once I get to know you I love to cuddle and will follow you around everywhere that you go. Crate training and having the proper amount of daily exercise are both really working out great for me, and I can’t wait to find my forever home. 

If you’re interested in learning more about Decker please submit an adoption application on our website www.loveatfirstmutt.org
